      <div class="container margin-top20">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-xs-12">
            <hr class="dashed-client">
            <h2 class="">Adjustments</h2>
            <p class="intro">Components are designed to sit within the padding area of a column, so that they align with the text. If you wish them to push out of that and either fill a column or a row width then add the following classes. </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row bg-grey04">
          <div class="col-xs-12">
            <h4>Full width of a row</h4>
            <p>These have a class of <strong>full-row</strong> added to the perf or hr.</p>
           <div class="perf perf-client full-row"></div>
           <hr class="client-dashed full-row">
          </div> <!-- / col -->
        </div> <!-- / row -->
      </div> <!-- / container -->

      <div class="container margin-top20">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-xs-12 bg-grey04">
            <h4>Full width of a column</h4>
            <p>These have a class of <strong>full-col</strong> added to the perf or hr.</p>
           <div class="perf perf-client full-col"></div>
           <hr class="client-dashed full-col">
          </div> <!-- / col -->
        </div> <!-- / row -->
      </div> <!-- / container -->

      <div class="container margin-top40">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-xs-12">
            
            <h4 class="">Container Fluid</h4>
            <p>Usually you would use Container-fluid to make something full width of the screen. However, occasionally you would want to keep a component within a container, but force it to breakout and appear as if it is in a container-fluid.</p>
            <p>This first example is of Perforations within a container-fluid.</p>
          </div> <!-- / col -->
        </div> <!-- / row -->
      </div> <!-- / container -->

      <div class="container-fluid">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-xs-12">
           <div class="perf"></div>
           <hr class="dashed">
          </div> <!-- / col -->
        </div> <!-- / row -->
      </div> <!-- / container-fluid -->

      <div class="container margin-top20">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-xs-12">
            <h4>Breakout of a container</h4>
            <p>If you wish a component to remain within a container (and not a container-fluid), but want them to appear full width of the browser window, then add the class of <strong>breakout</strong> to them.</p>
           <div class="perf perf-client breakout"></div>
           <hr class="dashed-client breakout">
          </div> <!-- / col -->
        </div> <!-- / row -->
      </div> <!-- / container -->

      <div class="container margin-top20">
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-xs-12">
            <p>This also works with other components like panels.</p>
            <p class="strong">Note: The breakout class need to be added to the component and not the container, row or column.</p>
           <div class="panel panel-default breakout">
              <div class="panel-heading">Panel heading without title</div>
              <div class="panel-body">
                Panel body
              </div>
            </div>
          </div> <!-- / col -->
        </div> <!-- / row -->
      </div> <!-- / container -->

